      <p class="kicker">The Guide &middot; Act One</p>
      <h1>Act One: the temptation</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        A play about the murder of a king spends its whole first act on a decision. Prophecy
        arrives, ambition wakes, and a soldier praised for loyalty argues himself, and is argued,
        into the one act his world has no word bad enough for. By the last line, nothing has been
        killed but the hero&rsquo;s scruples.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">What happens</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene One (an open place, in thunder and lightning).</strong> The three witches
        meet only long enough to fix their next meeting, on the heath, with Macbeth, before the
        battle&rsquo;s end. Their chant collapses opposites into one another and hands the play
        its keynote: a world in which the moral compass has been reversed and nothing can be
        taken at face value.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Two (a camp near Forres).</strong> Duncan receives news of the fighting. A
        wounded captain, and then Ross, describe Macbeth cutting through a rebel and an invading
        army with terrifying skill. Delighted, the king strips the treacherous Thane of Cawdor of
        his title and his life and gives the honour to Macbeth, who does not yet know he has been
        promoted.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Three (a heath).</strong> The witches boast of small cruelties, then stop
        Macbeth and Banquo on their way from the field. They greet Macbeth by three names, the
        last of them king, and promise Banquo a line of kings although he will wear no crown. The
        vision seems to dissolve, until Ross arrives and names Macbeth Thane of Cawdor. One
        prophecy has come true within minutes, and Macbeth is already picturing the murder that
        might make the rest come true.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Four (the palace at Forres).</strong> Duncan hears how calmly the old
        Cawdor met his execution and reflects that a traitor&rsquo;s heart cannot be read in his
        face. He thanks Macbeth and Banquo, then names his own son Malcolm his heir. Macbeth, who
        had half-hoped the crown might fall to him without effort, registers the boy as an
        obstacle and quietly asks the darkness to hide what he now wants.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Five (Macbeth&rsquo;s castle at Inverness).</strong> Lady Macbeth reads her
        husband&rsquo;s letter reporting the prophecy. She fears he is too decent to take the
        short way to the throne, and resolves to talk the courage into him herself. Told that
        Duncan will sleep under her roof that very night, she calls on spirits to empty her of
        tenderness and fill her with cruelty, and greets her husband already in command of the
        plan.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Six (before the castle).</strong> Duncan and his court arrive, and the king
        remarks on how sweet and welcoming the air of the place is. Lady Macbeth meets him with
        polished, overflowing courtesy. Every gracious word is a lie the audience can see through,
        and the gap between what is said and what is planned is the whole point of the scene.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Seven (a room in the castle).</strong> Left alone, Macbeth reasons his way
        through the murder and decides against it: Duncan is his king, his kinsman and his guest,
        a good ruler, and Macbeth has nothing driving him but ambition. Lady Macbeth returns and
        overturns the decision, attacking his manhood, brushing aside his conscience, and laying
        out exactly how the grooms will be drugged and blamed. He surrenders and commits.
      </p>

      <h2>A closer look</h2>

      <h3>The shape of temptation: soliloquy, staging and dramatic irony</h3>
      <p>
        Act One is built out of two kinds of scene set against each other, and the meaning lives
        in the contrast. In public, the play speaks in ceremonious verse: battle reports, royal
        thanks, the granting of titles, the courtesies of a king arriving as a guest. In private,
        it drops into soliloquy and aside, and this is where the actual plot advances, because
        the real event of the act is not a battle or a banquet but a change of mind. Shakespeare
        gives the audience the inside of Macbeth&rsquo;s head before he gives it to anyone on
        stage, and that privileged access is what makes the whole act unbearable to watch: we are
        made accomplices to a decision no other character can see forming.
      </p>
      <p>
        Watch how the ordering of the scenes does the arguing. Scene Six sets Duncan admiring the
        &lsquo;pleasant seat&rsquo; of the castle, praising its sweet air, trusting his host
        completely, while the audience carries into every kind word the murder plotted in the
        scene before and about to be sealed in the scene after. That is dramatic irony working
        structurally, not as a single ironic line but as an entire scene the audience hears in a
        register the characters cannot. The soliloquy that opens Scene Seven then does something
        rarer: it lets us watch a man reach the <em>right</em> conclusion, decide not to kill, and
        it is precisely because he gets there honestly that his reversal minutes later lands as
        tragedy rather than villainy. Form is not decoration here. The arrangement of public
        surface and private depth is the argument that a kingdom can look serene while its centre
        rots.
      </p>

      <h3>Equivocation and the witches</h3>
      <p>
        The witches barely appear in Act One, and they never once tell Macbeth to murder anyone.
        Their power is subtler and more Jacobean than that: they deal in truths that are true and
        still destroy the person who believes them. &lsquo;Fair is foul, and foul is fair&rsquo;
        (Act 1, Scene 1) is not nonsense but a working instruction for how to read the play, a
        chiasmus that folds good and evil into each other so that no appearance can be trusted.
        When Macbeth&rsquo;s first words on stage, &lsquo;So foul and fair a day I have not
        seen&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 3), unknowingly echo the witches&rsquo; rhythm, the play has
        already tuned him to their frequency before he has met them.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is where the historical context adds to the effect rather than being bolted on. Macbeth
        was written in the shadow of the 1605 Gunpowder Plot and the equivocation trials of 1606,
        at which the Jesuit Henry Garnet was condemned for defending equivocation, the practice of
        answering truthfully in words while deceiving in meaning. A Jacobean audience, primed by
        James&rsquo;s own <em>Daemonologie</em> and the 1604 witchcraft statute to see demonic
        agency as real and deceptive, would recognise the witches as equivocators in exactly that
        sense. Crucially, Macbeth learns their method and turns it inward. &lsquo;This supernatural
        soliciting cannot be ill, cannot be good&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 3) shows him already
        equivocating with himself, splitting a plain moral fact into a debate. The tragedy is not
        that the witches lie to him. It is that they tell him just enough truth for his own mind
        to supply the crime.
      </p>

      <h3>The seduction into regicide and Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s invented power</h3>
      <p>
        Macbeth does not decide to kill Duncan alone; he is talked into it, and the person who
        does the talking has to invent the power to do so. When Lady Macbeth fears her husband is
        &lsquo;too full o&rsquo; th&rsquo; milk of human kindness&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 5), she
        turns kindness itself into a defect, redefining decency as weakness and cruelty as
        strength. But notice what her great invocation admits. &lsquo;Come, you spirits that tend
        on mortal thoughts, unsex me here&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 5) is a request, not a boast: she
        does not possess the ruthlessness the murder needs, she has to summon it, and to do so she
        must have her womanhood taken from her. &lsquo;Come to my woman&rsquo;s breasts, and take
        my milk for gall&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 5) turns the body that nurtures into a body that
        poisons, which tells us the cruelty is not native to her but grafted on.
      </p>
      <p>
        Read through a feminist lens, this is a woman who has correctly understood that her world
        gives power only to men, and who therefore tries to unmake her own gender to reach it. Her
        weapon in Scene Seven is masculinity: she wins the argument not with reasons but by
        accusing Macbeth of cowardice, insisting that to be a man is to be willing to kill.
        Shakespeare lets her win, and lets her be magnificent doing it, which is why the moment is
        frightening rather than simply wicked. Yet the very effort of the invocation
        plants the seed of Act Five. Power that has to be conjured against your own nature is
        borrowed power, and borrowed power comes due. The hand that here calls for direst cruelty
        is the hand that will later rub itself raw trying to wash out a stain no one else can see.
      </p>

