      <div class="box think">
        <h3>Think it through</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>The witches never instruct Macbeth to murder. Does that make them more or less responsible for what follows, and how far can a production push their influence before it lets Macbeth off the hook?</li>
          <li>In Scene Seven Macbeth reaches the right decision and then abandons it. Is he seduced, or does he want to be? Where exactly does the responsibility sit?</li>
          <li>Lady Macbeth has to ask spirits to &lsquo;unsex&rsquo; her. If her cruelty must be summoned, is she powerful or trapped, and what does the play think a woman must give up to reach power?</li>
          <li>Why does Shakespeare place Duncan&rsquo;s praise of the castle&rsquo;s sweet air (Scene Six) between the plotting of the murder and its final decision? What does the ordering do to us?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="box exam">
        <h3>Towards the coursework</h3>
        <p>
          Act One is where all three set questions are seeded. On <strong>kingship</strong>, notice
          that Duncan is defined by trust, gratitude and generous ceremony, the very qualities that
          make him easy to murder, so that the play can ask whether goodness and effective rule are
          the same thing. On the <strong>presentation of women</strong>, Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s
          invocation gives you a woman who must unmake her gender to act, which is an argument, not
          just a character. On <strong>masculinity</strong>, watch how Scene Seven makes manhood the
          decisive weapon: Lady Macbeth wins by redefining being a man as being willing to kill, and
          Macbeth yields to that definition. Your task now: choose one of the three questions, take
          two quotations from the table above, and for each write a single sentence that moves from
          method to effect to a claim about the question, with a contextual angle folded into the
          claim rather than tacked on the end. Keep those sentences; they are the first bricks of
          your essay. Build the argument on the <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

